<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Of the 11 species included in this genus, four are recorded from China: 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Ophthalmothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophthalmothrips formosanus" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">Ophthalmothrips formosanus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Ophthalmothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophthalmothrips longiceps" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiceps">Ophthalmothrips longiceps</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Ophthalmothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophthalmothrips miscanthicola" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miscanthicola">Ophthalmothrips miscanthicola</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Ophthalmothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophthalmothrips yunnanensis" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yunnanensis">Ophthalmothrips yunnanensis</taxonomicName>
. This last species was based on one female and three males, and the description indicates that it is unusual in having the tergal wing-retaining setae small and straight in macropterae (
<bibRefCitation author="Cao, SJ" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="263 - 268" title="The genus Ophthalmothrips Hood (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae) from Mainland China with description of one New Species." url="10.3157/061.136.0310" volume="136" year="2010">Cao et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Ophthalmothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophthalmothrips formosanus" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">Ophthalmothrips formosanus</taxonomicName>
is here newly recorded from mainland China, in Henan Province.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Head longer than broad, projecting in front of eyes; eyes distinctly prolonged ventrally; 1 pair of postoculars well developed, 1 pair of interocellar setae elongate; stylets short, V-shaped; antennae 8-segmented, segment III with 2 sensoria, IV with 2 or 4; pronotum usually with 4 pairs of major setae, anteromarginals short, notopleural sutures complete; basantra present; mesopraesternum developed; metathoracic sternopleural sutures absent; fore wings, if well developed, with duplicated cilia; fore tarsal tooth present or absent; pelta broadly triangular; abdominal tergites 
<normalizedToken originalValue="IIâ€“VII">II-VII</normalizedToken>
usually each with 2 pairs of sigmoid wing-retaining setae; tube smooth without lateral setae; anal setae various.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
